<script src="./js/exceljs.js" charset="utf-8"></script>

<script>
	var inputBox = document.getElementById("inputBox");
	inputBox.addEventListener("change",function(){
	var reader = new FileReader();
	reader.readAsDataURL(inputBox.files[0]);
	reader.onload = function(){
		console.log(this.result);
		const wb = new ExcelJS.Workbook();
		wb.xlsx.load(this.result, {base64: true})
		.then(()=>{
			wb.xlsx.writeBuffer()
			.then((buf) => {
				saveAs(new Blob([buf]), 'outFileName.xlsx');
			})
		})
	}
	})
</script>
```

Named ranges with the same name on different pages - previous ranges will be lost, only the last range will remain

If anyone else has trouble creating a Workbook with definedNames with a localSheetId (so have the scope only applied to a specific sheet), there is a workaround you can apply:
```ts
const definedNamesModel = workbook.definedNames.model;
Object.defineProperty(workbook.definedNames, 'model', {
  set: function (x: typeof definedNamesModel) { (this as { _model: typeof definedNamesModel })._model = x; },
  get: function () { return (this as { _model: typeof definedNamesModel })._model; }
});

workbook.definedNames.model = [
  ...definedNamesModel,
  { name: 'example', ranges: [`'${sheet.name.replace("'", "''")}'!$A$1`], localSheetId: sheet.id - 1 }
]
```
This works because the XML definedNames renderer then uses now the correct/ unmodified model.
